Fig 4 Types of porches and entry ways

A Roofed porch

C Vaulted entry way

See how to measure height of porches &
entry features in Figs 6-8 on pp. 11-13

B Roofed entry way
(not vaulted)

D Combination porch & vaulted entry way

visual_elements.description: Line drawing of a single-story house with a front porch supported by four columns. The porch has a gabled roof. Labeled 'A Roofed porch'.

Line drawing of a two-story house with a central vaulted entry way. The entry way has a gabled roof and a large arched double door. Two dormer windows are visible on the roof. A vertical measurement line indicates 'Height greater than 12' above grade' from the ground to the top of the roofline. Labeled 'C Vaulted entry way'.

Line drawing of a two-story house with a small, gabled entry way on the right side. The entry way has a single arched door. A vertical measurement line indicates 'Height less than 12' above grade' from the ground to the top of the entry way roof. Labeled 'B Roofed entry way (not vaulted)'.

Line drawing of a structure combining a porch and a vaulted entry way. The porch section on the left has three arched openings supported by columns. The right section is a vaulted entry way with an arched door and a gabled roof. A vertical measurement line indicates 'Height greater than 12' above grade' from the ground to the top of the roofline. Labeled 'D Combination porch & vaulted entry way'.
